{
  "artist": {
    "name": "Chaos of Zen",
    "bio": "Chaos of Zen is the recording name of Joe Chavez, a Reno, Nevada-based artist working in generative, ambient, and improvised electronic music. His earliest musical memory traces back to a record player his parents gave him one Christmas, which sent him traveling through decades of music — early rock and roll, the 60s, 70s, and 80s — and on to a lifelong pull toward live shows.\n\nHis touchstones as a listener are Radiohead's OK Computer, Rage Against the Machine's self-titled debut, and U2's No Line on the Horizon (Bonus Track Version) — three records he returns to for the way they hold up in live performance: OK Computer for its sophistication, Rage Against the Machine for its unbridled passion, and No Line on the Horizon as the culmination of U2's decades-long evolution.\n\nAmong his own recordings, he singles out “Eight-02.26” — eight hands on four pianos, simple on the surface but built from decades of experimentation in ambient, generative, and improvised music. The recording captures a single point in time within an ever-evolving composition.",
